## Rule Hierarchy

This file applies to **every** edit. Before starting any task, identify which scoped rule(s) apply and load them. When in doubt, load the rule — it is always better to over-load than to miss one.

- [ac.mdc](ac.mdc) — Acceptance Criteria standard (always applied; applies to every Linear issue and prompt)
- [agents.mdc](agents.mdc) — Agent/prompt lifecycle, STOP protocol, model selection (always applied)
- [backend.mdc](backend.mdc) — Load when touching `api-gateway/`, `handbrake-service/`, `shared/`, or any `.py`
- [frontend.mdc](frontend.mdc) — Load when touching anything under `ui-frontend/`
- [devops.mdc](devops.mdc) — Load when touching `Dockerfile*`, `docker-compose*.yml`, `deployment/`, `.github/`, `terraform/`, or any `.sh`

### When to load [frontend.mdc](frontend.mdc)
- Editing any file under `ui-frontend/`
- Writing or modifying React components, hooks, CSS, Vite, Tailwind, or PostCSS config
- Implementing a UI feature that consumes API data
- Importing or modifying Magic Patterns components
- Running any browser verification step (Playwright, screenshot, CSS sanity)

### When to load [backend.mdc](backend.mdc)
- Editing any file under `api-gateway/`, `handbrake-service/`, or `shared/`
- Writing Python code (any `.py` file)
- Creating or modifying a database migration (`.sql` file in `migrations/`)
- Designing or changing an API endpoint, request schema, or response shape
- Debugging a server-side error (logs, stack traces, DB queries)
- Writing or running tests against the API

### When to load [devops.mdc](devops.mdc)
- Editing any `Dockerfile`, `docker-compose*.yml`, or `.env*` file
- Editing any file under `deployment/`, `terraform/`, or `.github/`
- Writing or modifying a shell script (`.sh`)
- Running `terraform plan`, `terraform apply`, or any `gcloud` command
- Deploying to any environment
- Creating or modifying a GitHub Actions workflow (`.github/workflows/*.yml`)
- Performing a DB backup, restore, or migration on a live environment
- Checking disk space, pruning Docker resources, or managing server processes

## Personas & Process
Use personas where appropriate: **product manager, front-end engineer, back-end engineer, full-stack engineer, engineering manager, project manager, QA engineer**. When creating prompts, select relevant ones and iterate between them **in sequence**, not parallel.

- Read documentation before creating prompts or Linear issues and before writing code.
- Update documentation at the end of each prompt or issue.
- No documentation may be orphaned: every doc must be referenced (with path) in [README.md](../../README.md) or a rule file.
- When a mistake pattern is clear during development, recommend an update to the relevant rule file.

## Critical Thinking
- **Prioritize truth over agreement.** Be a critical partner; analyze assumptions; test reasoning; provide alternate solutions.
- Correct clearly and explain why when anyone (user or agent) is wrong.
- Do not claim "ready for production" if it is not.

## Code Quality
- **DRY and SRP**: No duplicated blocks >3 lines; one clear purpose per function/class; shared logic in reusable helpers; follow project ESLint/Prettier conventions.
- **Official docs first**: Consult official documentation before implementing any feature or making assumptions (Google Cloud, Mailgun, PostgreSQL, Python libraries, Docker, Kubernetes, Terraform). Do not rely on third-party tutorials or outdated blog posts.
- **Environment variables**: Use env vars for secrets, host names, ports, and parameters; never hardcode.

## File and Folder Organization
- **No files in the repo root** — everything in respective folders (exceptions: `README.md`, standard config files like `.gitignore`, `package.json` scope files).
- **No duplicate folders** — check existing structure before creating new folders. If you find duplicates, report and recommend consolidation.
- **Pattern**: `[service-name]/[function-name]/`. Tests live in a subfolder (e.g. `[function-name]/unit-tests`). If you produce >5 unrelated files of the same kind (e.g. deployment scripts), group them in a folder (e.g. `deployment/`).
- **One central `migrations/` folder** for the project — never create additional migration folders.
- **File versioning**: Use zero-padded versions (`deploy001.sh`, `deploy002.sh`) — never ad-hoc names like `deploy_new.sh`, `deploy_simple.sh`.
- **Prompts live in** `docs/prompts/`. Completed prompts move to `docs/prompts/completed prompts/` with a `done__` prefix (see [agents.mdc](agents.mdc) § Prompt Lifecycle).

## Security (Git)
- **Max 10 MB per file**; max 100 MB per repo.
- **Never commit** passwords, API keys, tokens, credentials, `.env` files, database dumps, or private certificates.
- Before every commit, grep for secret patterns: `password`, `api_key`, `secret`, `token`, `credential`.
- If sensitive data is accidentally committed: **stop, notify the user, and await approval** before history rewrite (`git filter-branch` / BFG).

## Linear Project Management
- **Only touch Linear issues in the `handbrake2resilio` project.** Never modify issues on other projects.
- **All Linear issues you create must be in the `handbrake2resilio` project.**
- **When the user reports a bug**: immediately create a Linear issue in `handbrake2resilio` with `priority: 1` (Urgent) or `priority: 2` (High) and a `Bug` label. Confirm the issue URL.
- **When the user gives a feature idea**: immediately create a Linear issue with `priority: 3` (Normal) and a `Feature` label. Confirm the issue URL.
- **Trigger phrases** (case-insensitive) that should auto-create a Linear issue:
  - Bug: "bug", "broken", "not working", "issue with", "error", "crash", "fix", "regression"
  - Feature: "idea", "recommendation", "suggestion", "we should", "would be nice", "add", "improve", "enhancement", "future"
- **Don't ask before creating** — just create and report back.
- **Create subtasks** for all parts of a story (PRs, deploy, docs) so closure really means "done".
- **Every issue must have acceptance criteria** — see [ac.mdc](ac.mdc).
- **Every issue must have a recommended LLM model** — see [agents.mdc](agents.mdc) § Model Selection. Before starting an issue, verify the active model matches the recommendation.

## Issue Log

The canonical recurring-bug log lives at [`docs/standards/ISSUE_LOG.md`](../../docs/standards/ISSUE_LOG.md).

### Mandatory agent actions
- **On closing a bug**: Check whether the bug matches an existing category in `ISSUE_LOG.md`. If yes, add a row (issue ID, date, title, root cause, prevention added). If no, note it in the Open Items section.
- **On pattern recurrence** (same root cause, 2+ issues): Create a new `## CAT-N` section in the log, back-fill all matching issues, and add a prevention rule to the relevant `.mdc` file in the same PR.
- **On adding a prevention rule**: Record the rule reference in the `Prevention Added` column of every affected row.
- **Trigger phrases** that should prompt a log check: "same issue", "again", "regression", "still broken", "also broken", "duplicate".

## Git Branch Strategy

### Branches
- **`master` / `main`**: Stable, deployable branch. Never push directly; merge via PR.
- **Feature/fix branches** (e.g. `fix/voice-bug`, `feat/css-sanity`): short-lived, branch from `master`, merged via PR back to `master` after review.
- **Dev branches** (if used): When on a dev branch, check which branch is active and do not create a new one unless there is a specific need.

### Rules
- **Default**: Branch from `master`. Merge via PR; never commit directly to `master` for work spanning multiple prompts or >2 domains.
- **Naming**: `feat/`, `fix/`, `chore/`, `docs/` prefixes. Zero-pad phases: `feat/phase-052-playwright-ci`.
- **Branch verification**: Run `git branch --show-current` immediately before any `git add` / `git commit` and confirm it matches the intended branch. If it doesn't, unstage with `git restore --staged .`, switch branches, then re-stage.
- **Never rebuild anything directly — always rebuild the container.** Incremental container updates are forbidden; always do full clean rebuilds (see [devops.mdc](devops.mdc) § Clean Deployment).

## Cross-references — Most-Skipped Rules (repeated here because core.mdc is always loaded)

These rules exist in scoped files but are frequently skipped by agents. They are repeated here as hard reminders.

### 1. Category-Binding Gate ([ac.mdc](ac.mdc) § Category-Binding Gate)
If an issue touches a domain covered by a CAT in [`docs/standards/ISSUE_LOG.md`](../../docs/standards/ISSUE_LOG.md), its AC **MUST** include the matching prevention checklist from the relevant rule file. An issue that maps to a CAT but omits the checklist is defective. Same rule applies to prompts — see [agents.mdc](agents.mdc) § Category-Aware Prompt Gate.

### 2. HTTP 200 is Not Sufficient ([devops.mdc](devops.mdc) § Post-deploy API Contract Verification)
After every deploy, assert **data shape**, not just HTTP status. A green health check with a broken response body is a failed deploy.

### 3. CSS Sanity Is Required On Every Frontend Build ([frontend.mdc](frontend.mdc) § CSS Sanity)
"No JS errors" is NOT sufficient — an unstyled app has zero JS errors. Every Playwright smoke run MUST assert `document.styleSheets[0].cssRules.length > 50` OR that the built CSS bundle is >5 KB, AND take a full-page screenshot for human review.

### 4. Playwright Runs In Docker, Never On Host ([frontend.mdc](frontend.mdc) § Playwright Containerization)
Never install Playwright system dependencies on the host. Always run tests inside `mcr.microsoft.com/playwright`, using the project's `ui-frontend/Dockerfile.playwright`.

### 5. Frontend Dockerfile Explicit COPY ([frontend.mdc](frontend.mdc) § Frontend Dockerfile)
Never `COPY . .`. Before `RUN npm run build`, explicitly `COPY` every `*.config.js` (`tailwind.config.js`, `postcss.config.js`, `vite.config.js`). After build, verify the CSS bundle is >5 KB.

### 6. Magic Patterns Is Immutable ([frontend.mdc](frontend.mdc) § Magic Patterns)
Every Magic Patterns file has `/* MAGIC_PATTERNS_IMMUTABLE */` as its first line and lives in `ui-frontend/src/ui/magic-patterns/`. Never modify one without explicit user permission. Build wrappers, not replacements.

### 7. Deploy Permission Gate ([devops.mdc](devops.mdc) § Deployment Permission Gate)
**Never deploy to any environment without explicit user approval.** Applies to manual deploys and CI/CD triggers. Present a deploy plan and wait for a clear "go ahead".

